## Scales


<br>

*Example 6*.

Consider the following scale which we might use to rank applicants: (top 10%, top 20%, top 30%, top 40%).  Which of the following is a conversational implicature of the recommendation letter writer having said "The applicant is within the top 30% of her class"?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 Which is it?
| The letter writer does not believe that "The applicant is within the top 40% of her class"
| The letter writer does not believe that "The applicant is within the top 30% of her class"
| *The letter writer does not believe that "The applicant is within the top 20% of her class"
| *The letter writer does not believe that "The applicant is within the top 10% of her class"
```

<br>

*Example 7*.

Consider the following scale which we might use to informally rank universities: (prestigious, excellent, good, decent).  Which of the following is a conversational implicature of someone saying that "This campus is not good"? *Hint*: when we negate entries, the scale flips around.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 Which is it?
| The speaker does not believe that "The campus is not prestigious"
| The speaker does not believe that "The campus is not excellent"
| The speaker does not believe that "The campus is not good"
| *The speaker does not believe that "The campus is not decent"
```


<br>

*Example 8*.

Show the following:

```{.ProofChecker .GamutPNDPlus submission="none"}
  ~(a\/b)  :|-: ~(a/\b)
|~(a\/b) :assumption
```

<br>


*Example 9*.

Determine whether the argument is valid or invalid:

```{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" submission="none" options="nodash autoAtoms"}
 ~(a/\b) :|-: ~(a\/b)
```

<br>

*Example 10*.

The previous example suggests a scale (~(a\/b), ~(a/\b)). Which of the following is a conversational implicature of the speaker having said that "It's not the case that Alex and Brianna attended"?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 Which one?
| The speaker believes that "Alex attended and Brianna attended"
| The speaker does not believe "It's not the case that Alex attended and Brianna attended"
| The speaker does not believe "Alex attended or Brianna attended"
| *The speaker does not believe "It's not the case that Alex attended or Brianna attended"
```

