```

<br>

*Example 14*

Suppose that you know that the probability of p is 25% and the probability of q is 25% and that the probability of p\/q is 40%. What is the probability of p/\q?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is the probability of p/\q?
| 5%
| 6.25%
| *10%
| 30%
```

<br>

*Example 15*

Suppose that you know that the probability of p is 25% and the probability of q is 25% and that the probability of p\/q is 40%. What is the probability of $\neg p \wedge \neg q$? *Hint*: use DeMorgan.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is the probability of ~p/\~q?
| 50%
| *60%
| 70%
| 80%
```

